<ArticleLayout
  lang="en"
  altPath="/blog/lich-su-tam-ly-hoc/"
  title="A history of psychology through its questions about the mind | An Nhịp"
  description="A timeline of psychological thought: from Yogācāra and the 1879 Leipzig laboratory through psychoanalysis and behaviourism to CBT and cognitive science, marking clearly what is historical influence and what remains contested."
  heading="A history of psychology through its questions about the mind"
  datePublished="2026-07-22"
  sources={sources}
>
  <p>
    Psychology did not develop in a straight line. The schools below are placed
    side by side to reveal the enduring questions about consciousness, selfhood,
    behaviour, meaning and change. They are not "facts" verified to the same
    degree, and this page says so at every entry.
  </p>

  <h2>How to read this page</h2>
  <p>
    The Yogācāra tradition is Buddhist philosophy and psychology, not a direct
    precursor of experimental psychology. Psychoanalysis, existential and
    humanistic schools carry enormous cultural and clinical influence, yet many
    of their propositions cannot be treated as current scientific evidence.
  </p>
  <p>
    Every figure comes with a caveat note in the margin voice, setting out what
    belongs to historical influence and what has not been confirmed. Hypotheses
    that remain genuinely contested are flagged separately.
  </p>

  <div class="era">
    <p class="era-date">c. 4th to 5th century CE</p>
    <h2>Classical Buddhist psychology</h2>
    <p class="era-intro">
      Rather than "ancient psychology" in general, this marker refers to the
      consolidation of the Yogācāra tradition in India, a philosophically deep
      system for analysing experience and cognition.
    </p>
    <div class="figures">
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">V</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Asaṅga and Vasubandhu</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">
            Yogācāra · India, c. 4th to 5th century CE
          </p>
          <p>
            Yogācāra develops a model of <strong>eight consciousnesses</strong>,
            in which <em>ālaya-vijñāna</em> is often rendered "storehouse
            consciousness" or "foundational consciousness", while
            <em>manas</em> is tied to self-grasping. The system describes how
            experience, habitual tendencies and cognition together construct the
            world as it is lived.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            Do not equate ālaya-vijñāna with the Freudian unconscious, or with a
            "hard drive" storing memories in a neuroscientific sense. These
            belong to different metaphysical and soteriological frameworks.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="era">
    <p class="era-date">1879 · Leipzig</p>
    <h2>Psychology separates from philosophy</h2>
    <p class="era-intro">
      This is the marker usually taken as the beginning of psychology as an
      independent experimental science: studying the mind through controlled
      measurement rather than philosophical argument alone.
    </p>
    <div class="figures">
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">W</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Wilhelm Wundt</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">
            Experimental psychology · 1832-1920, Leipzig laboratory 1879
          </p>
          <p>
            Wundt founded the first laboratory devoted specifically to
            psychological research at the University of Leipzig, trained a
            generation of researchers, and established psychology as a
            discipline with methods of its own. He used
            <strong>controlled introspection</strong> under experimental
            conditions to examine immediate conscious experience, such as
            sensation and reaction time.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            The label "father of psychology" is a simplification. Wundt himself
            held that higher mental processes such as language, myth and custom
            could not be studied experimentally, and spent years writing
            <em>Völkerpsychologie</em> to approach them by other methods.
            Introspection was later heavily criticised by behaviourism and
            largely abandoned in experimental psychology.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="era">
    <p class="era-date">Late 19th century</p>
    <h2>Crowds, consciousness and evolutionary stories</h2>
    <p class="era-intro">
      This period contains both influential social research and bold
      conjectures about the origins of consciousness. Their value lies in
      opening questions, not in having been confirmed as a history of the brain.
    </p>
    <div class="figures">
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">J</div>
        <div>
          <p class="figure-flag">Contested hypothesis</p>
          <h3>Julian Jaynes</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">
            1920-1997 · <em>The Origin of Consciousness</em> (1976)
          </p>
          <p>
            The <strong>bicameral mind</strong> theory proposes that
            introspection may have developed relatively late, and that ancient
            people experienced "voices" as commands coming from outside.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            This is a fascinating interdisciplinary hypothesis, but it is not
            accepted as consensus in neuroscience, archaeology or the psychology
            of consciousness.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">L</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Gustave Le Bon</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">
            Early social psychology · 1841-1931, <em>The Crowd</em> (1895)
          </p>
          <p>
            Le Bon popularised an influential theory of crowds: anonymity,
            emotional contagion and suggestibility can alter individual
            behaviour.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            The claim that crowds are "inevitably stupid and violent" reflects
            Le Bon's own period prejudices, not the conclusions of contemporary
            crowd psychology. Modern research emphasises social identity, norms
            and context.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="era">
    <p class="era-date">1900 to 1950</p>
    <h2>Psychoanalysis: conflict, purpose and symbol</h2>
    <p class="era-intro">
      These three did not belong to one school. They split over a deeper
      argument: is a person shaped by drives, by social purpose, or by symbols
      and processes of maturation?
    </p>
    <div class="figures">
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">F</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Sigmund Freud</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">Psychoanalysis · 1856-1939</p>
          <p>
            The structural model of <strong>Id, Ego and Superego</strong>
            describes conflict between drive, adjustment to reality and the
            internalising of norms. Freud also emphasised the role of early
            experience and unconscious processes.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            The "iceberg" is a popular illustration, not the whole theory.
            Thanatos appears later (1920), while the Id, Ego and Superego model
            was systematised in 1923. Many Freudian propositions are not
            supported empirically by modern standards.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">A</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Alfred Adler</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">Individual psychology · 1870-1937</p>
          <p>
            Adler emphasised purposiveness, lifestyle, feelings of inferiority
            and the striving for growth. He held that people are interpreting,
            goal-directed agents rather than merely pushed along by their past.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            Social feeling (<em>Gemeinschaftsgefühl</em>) is a central ethical
            and developmental criterion in Adler's system, not a standardised
            clinical measure.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">J</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Carl Jung</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">Analytical psychology · 1875-1961</p>
          <p>
            Jung introduced <strong>persona</strong>, <strong>shadow</strong>,
            the archetypes and <strong>individuation</strong>, a process
            oriented toward integrating psychological life. These ideas remain
            influential in depth therapy, culture and art criticism.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            The "collective unconscious" and the archetypes do not have the
            status of demonstrated neural structures. Read them as a framework
            for interpreting symbols, not as a biological map of the brain.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="era">
    <p class="era-date">1940 to 1970</p>
    <h2>Behaviour, meaning, growth and the relational self</h2>
    <p class="era-intro">
      From laws of learning to the question of what makes a life worth living,
      these directions shifted the focus from explaining pathology toward
      observing behaviour, choice, meaning and developmental needs.
    </p>
    <div class="figures">
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">S</div>
        <div>
          <h3>B. F. Skinner</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">Behaviourism · 1904-1990</p>
          <p>
            Skinner developed operant conditioning: the consequences of
            behaviour, such as reinforcement and extinction, change the
            probability of that behaviour in future. This work underpins applied
            behaviour analysis.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            He criticised metaphysical conceptions of free will, but research on
            conditioning does not "prove" that human beings are machines without
            choice.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">F</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Viktor Frankl</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">Existential and logotherapy · 1905-1997</p>
          <p>
            After surviving imprisonment in Nazi concentration camps, Frankl
            developed <strong>logotherapy</strong>: a person can find or create
            meaning even within adversity, and retains a margin of freedom in
            their attitude.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            Meaning is the philosophical and therapeutic pillar of Frankl's
            work. It should not be used to imply that people who are suffering
            are at fault for "not having found meaning".
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">M</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Abraham Maslow</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">Humanistic psychology · 1908-1970</p>
          <p>
            Maslow studied motivation, needs and
            <strong>self-actualisation</strong>, helping bring positive
            qualities and human potential into psychology.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            The "pyramid of needs" is a later popularisation, not a diagram
            Maslow drew. The rigidity of the hierarchy and its claimed
            universality face substantial cross-cultural criticism.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">K</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Heinz Kohut and Otto Kernberg</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">
            Self psychology, object relations · Kohut 1913-1981, Kernberg born
            1928
          </p>
          <p>
            Kohut described "selfobject" needs and the development of the self.
            Kernberg studied borderline personality organisation, object
            relations and narcissistic pathology. The two proposed different
            models of pathological narcissism.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            These are psychodynamic theories, not the only explanation nor a
            verdict on anyone with narcissistic traits. Diagnosing narcissistic
            personality disorder requires careful clinical assessment, not
            inference from isolated behaviour.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="era">
    <p class="era-date">1955 to the present</p>
    <h2>Belief, intuition, the brain and the plasticity of change</h2>
    <p class="era-intro">
      Contemporary psychology is increasingly interdisciplinary. The better
      models tend to link cognition, learning, the body, relationships and
      context, rather than reducing everything to one "node" in the brain or a
      single law.
    </p>
    <div class="figures">
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">E</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Albert Ellis</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">REBT, forerunner of CBT · 1913-2007</p>
          <p>
            Ellis's rational emotive behaviour therapy (REBT), with its
            <strong>A, B, C</strong> framework, stresses that interpretation and
            belief contribute to emotional and behavioural consequences, not the
            event alone.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            The A, B, C framework does not mean emotions are always a "thinking
            error". Biology, society, trauma and real circumstances all matter.
            Modern CBT also has other branches, with Aaron Beck as another
            founding figure.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">B</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Aaron T. Beck</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">
            Cognitive therapy, foundation of CBT · 1921-2021
          </p>
          <p>
            Beck trained as a psychoanalyst, but his empirical research on
            depression did not match that theory's predictions. From there he
            built the <strong>cognitive model</strong>: automatic thoughts,
            distorted thinking patterns and core beliefs help maintain distress.
            He developed the <strong>thought record</strong>, the tool the
            thought journal in <a href={withBase('/en/')}>An Nhịp</a> descends
            from, along with measures such as the BDI and BAI.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            The cognitive model does not imply that emotions are merely
            "thinking errors". Beck himself stressed the role of biology, life
            circumstances and trauma. CBT has a strong evidence base for anxiety
            and depression, but it does not work for everyone and does not
            replace professional assessment and treatment where those are
            needed.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">K</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Daniel Kahneman</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">Judgment and decision making · 1934-2024</p>
          <p>
            With Amos Tversky, Kahneman clarified the heuristics and biases at
            work in judgment. The vocabulary of <strong>System 1</strong>, fast
            and automatic, and <strong>System 2</strong>, slow and effortful, is
            a highly useful descriptive tool.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            The two "systems" are not two separate brain regions, and the story
            that "reason is merely the secretary of emotion" is a metaphor
            stretched well beyond the actual research.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">S</div>
        <div>
          <p class="figure-flag">Contested</p>
          <h3>Steven Pinker and Robert Sapolsky</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">
            Evolution, neurobiology · Pinker born 1954, Sapolsky born 1957
          </p>
          <p>
            Both helped popularise a way of seeing behaviour across layers of
            time: developmental, endocrine, neural, social and evolutionary.
            Sapolsky argues for a strong determinist position, while Pinker is
            prominent in evolutionary psychology, language and cognitive
            science.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            Do not collapse these two authors into a single stance that "rejects
            free will". The free will question remains a philosophical and
            scientific debate. A biological explanation does not automatically
            erase responsibility, the capacity for change, or the influence of
            environment.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
      <article class="figure">
        <div class="figure-mark" aria-hidden="true">B</div>
        <div>
          <h3>Judson Brewer</h3>
          <p class="figure-dates">
            Mindfulness and neuroscience · physician and mindfulness researcher
          </p>
          <p>
            Brewer studies habit, addiction, mindfulness and brain networks,
            including the Default Mode Network (DMN). His work has helped bring
            the experience of mindfulness into dialogue with neuroscience.
          </p>
          <p class="caveat">
            There is no conclusion that "non-self" is a simple physical
            disconnection of the DMN. Neuroimaging results are correlational and
            method-dependent. Meditative experience cannot be reduced to a
            single brain network.
          </p>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>From a history of ideas to everyday practice</h2>
  <p>
    What is worth keeping from this history is not a winning theory but a habit:
    telling apart what you believe from what has actually been tested. That is
    exactly what a Beck-style thought record asks you to do with yourself, at
    the scale of one difficult afternoon.
  </p>
  <p>
    If you would rather start with concrete techniques than theory, these two
    short guides are immediately practical:
    <a href={withBase('/en/blog/breathing-exercises-for-anxiety/')}>breathing
    exercises for anxiety</a> and the
    <a href={withBase('/en/blog/5-4-3-2-1-grounding-technique/')}>5-4-3-2-1
    grounding technique</a>. Both are in the An Nhịp app, along with a CBT
    thought journal. Free, no account, and your data stays on your phone.
    <a href={withBase('/en/download/')}>Get the Android build here</a>.
  </p>
</ArticleLayout>

<style>
  /* History article, scoped. Extends the An Nhịp token system:
     no new tokens, no new radii, no motion. */

  .era {
    margin-block: clamp(3rem, 6vw, 4.5rem) 0;
  }

  .era > h2 {
    margin-top: 0.2rem;
  }

  /* Chronology is content here, not a decorative eyebrow. */
  .era-date {
    color: var(--sage);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    margin-bottom: 0.2rem;
  }

  .era-intro {
    color: var(--ink-2);
  }

  .figures {
    display: grid;
    gap: 1rem;
    margin-top: 1.75rem;
  }

  /* Same material as .card in global.css */
  .figure {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 3.25rem 1fr;
    gap: 1.25rem;
    align-items: start;
    padding: 1.5rem;
    background: var(--surface);
    border: 1px solid var(--line);
    border-radius: var(--radius-card);
  }

  /* Initial letter stands in for a portrait: licensing-safe and works offline */
  .figure-mark {
    display: grid;
    place-items: center;
    width: 3.25rem;
    height: 3.25rem;
    border-radius: var(--radius-ui);
    background: var(--sage-soft);
    color: var(--sage-dark);
    font-size: 1.4rem;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  .figure h3 {
    font-size: 1.15rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.1rem;
  }

  .figure-dates {
    color: var(--ink-2);
    font-size: 0.9rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.9rem;
  }

  /* Only for genuinely contested claims, never as decoration */
  .figure-flag {
    display: inline-block;
    margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
    padding: 0.1rem 0.5rem;
    border-radius: var(--radius-ui);
    background: var(--sage-soft);
    color: var(--sage-dark);
    font-size: 0.8rem;
    font-weight: 600;
  }

  /* Mirrors .prose blockquote so caveats read as a known voice.
     Amber stays reserved for the medical disclaimer. */
  .caveat {
    margin-top: 1rem;
    margin-bottom: 0;
    padding-left: 1rem;
    border-left: 3px solid var(--sage-deco);
    color: var(--ink-2);
    font-size: 0.95rem;
  }

  .figure p:last-child {
    margin-bottom: 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 640px) {
    .figure {
      grid-template-columns: 2.5rem 1fr;
      gap: 1rem;
      padding: 1.25rem;
    }

    .figure-mark {
      width: 2.5rem;
      height: 2.5rem;
      font-size: 1.1rem;
    }
  }
</style>
